{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_dioptase_ver02/data/sn92050145/00516990351/1930121201/0764.xml":{"full_text":"The Home of More Than 5,000 Working\nHen and Their Families\nNORTH LITTLE ROCK\n\u201cIndustrial City of the South\u201d\nMONTHLY SURVEY OF BUSINESS\nOf the American Federation of Labor\nNo. 18 December 1,1930\nBusiness Adjustments Proceed\nAfter a feeble attempt at recov\nery in September business has\nshrunk ptill further The usual fall\nbusy season did not reach normal\nproportions in October and prelim\ninary November reports show no\ngeneral upward trend. The auto\nmobile industry, which is generally\nconsidered a key to the situation,\nJOIN NOW\n\u2014A Christmas Savings at Our Bank\nWhen next Christmas rolls around, see to it that you\nhave sufficient money to insure a HAPPY Christmas.\n\u2014A Club for every member of the family. Come in\u2014\njoin with us today!\nSave Any Amount\u2014From 25c to $100 Weekly\u2014\n4 Per Cfcnt Interest\n200 Main\nNorth Little Reck\nreduced October production to\n157,000 cars, the lowest since 1921\nand less than half last year's Oc\ntober production. The steel indus\ntry finds demands very low be\ncause of this automobile slack, and\nalso because orders for rails have\nbeen less than one-third the aver\nage for recent years, pipe line\nbusiness is tapering off as winter\napproaches and orders for farm\nimplements have dropped. By No\nvember 8, steel operations had de\nclined to 4 4per cent of capacity.\nProduction of all industries drop\nped 3 per cent from September to\nOctober and business generally is\nnow 23 per cent below normal.\nOn the other hand, definite signs\nof improvement are multiplying in\nindividual lines. The upward turn\nin textiles, both silk and cotton, is\nencouraging. The textile industry\nwas one of the leaders in recovery\nfrom 1921- Building has improved\nslightly, department store sales in\ncreased more than seasonally in\nOctober (preliminary figures) and\nthere are signs that the price de\ncline is nearer bottom. Business\nmen are beginning to take out\nmore loans and order more ma\nchine tools, which means a prospect\nof improving efficiency and in\ncreasing operations. These are the I\ntype of changes, which when they\nincrease, will indicate business re\ncovery.\nWhile there are increaisng reas\nons to believe that an upturn is in\nEverybody Needs Money\nOccasionally\nDO YOU?\nThe business of fhis Company is to supply the needs of the wage\nearner, who may for any number of reasons, find that he requires\nfinancial assistance.\nPerhaps you have an insurance premium due\u2014perhaps there is a\npayment due on your home\u2014perhaps sickness has exacted an un*\nexpected toll\u2014perhaps there are some improvements on your\nhome that should be made-r-perhaps you require help in getting\nthat boy or girl through school, or perhaps through reasons be*\nyond your control, you have a number of small scattered obliga*\ntions that you would really like to meet in order to maintain your\ncredit standing.\nWhy Not Assemble These Debts and\nOwe One Place?\nLoans are made under our plan on the primary basis of character\nand earning capacity, at a rate sanctioned by the laws of our state\nand on terms adapted to the requirements of the average wage\nearner\u2014\nThe negotiations of a loan with this Com\npany is a simple, friendly and neighborly trans\naction, that is handled in a Business-like,\nprivate and dignified manner.\nThe terms o! our loans provide for tbeir retirement in convenient\nweekly, semi-monthly or monthly installments that work no hard\nship on the borrower, and yet automatically cancel the debt when\nthe loan matures.\nSuppose We Sit Down and Figure it Out?\nMutual Loan Investment Company\n106 South Cross Street\nA FRIENDLY INSTITUTION OF STRENGTH AND CHARACTER THAT\nSINCERELY DESIRES TO BE HELPFUL ALSO\nthe offing, there is no question\nthat the coming winter will be an\nexceedingly bard one. Business\nforecasters seem to unite in the be\nlief that spring will bring a defi\nnite change for the better. But the\nbest we can hope for winter is that\ndownward movement will not pro\nceed further.\nLooking Back Thirty Years\nSince the month of June, busi\nness has unquestionably declined\ninto a major depression.\nIn the last 30 years there have\nbeen five major depressions arid\nfive smaller ones* By comparing\nthe 1030 depression with the others\nit is clear that only once before has\nbusiness sunk to so low a level, and\nthat was in 1921.\nConsidering the 1930 depression\nmore closely, it is important to\nnote that if last spring\u2019s improve\nment had continued, we should\nhave had a minor depression like\n1914 and 1927. But certain factors\nin the situation worked against re\ncovery and helped to bring the\ndownward sweep in early summer\nwhich carried business swiftly into\na major depression. Important\namong these conditions were:\nBusiness depression in foreign\ncountries; the serious unemploy\nment of last winter; lack of organ,\nization to resist depression; install,\nment buying.\nInternational Business Depression\nHistory shows that all our major\ndepressions in the past have been\ninternational in character. The se\nvere business depression in nearly\nall foreign countries was a chief\nreason why business in America\ncould not recover last spring.\nAmerican business men and wage\nearners are not in the habit of\nthinking that conditions here are\nstrongly influenced by prosperity\nor depression abroad. But the real,\nization of our dependence on for\neign nations is at last gaining\nground*\nTwo important features of the\npresent situation have been the in\nternational decline of stock market\nvalues and wholesale prices of\n^commodities. The drop in,prices of\nAmerican farm products and man\nufactured goods which has checked\nbusiness progress for 15 months\nhas been greatly influenced by the\nworld wide decline of prices for\narticles passing in trade between\nnations. Figures for Germany, i\nEngland, Japan, Peru and a num-\nber of other countries, show for all i\na marked decline of wholesale I\nprices beginning in the spring or\nfall of 1929. These price declines\nare due largely to the fact that\nworld consumer buying power was\nnot large enough to purchase the\ncommodities produced by farmers\nand manufacturers. Low wage lev\nels in foreign countries and among\nmany groups of American wage\nearners are a dominating factor in\nthis failure of purchasing power.\nWithin the last few months there\nare a few signs which suggest im\nprovement in the international bus\niness situation. Prices are turning\nupward in Hungary and Egypt;\nBritish opinion looks to an upturn\nm the spring and the belief is that\ndepression has about reached bot\ntom. Retail trade in Britain was\nbetter in September and October\nand there is more interest in new\ncapital for business finance* But\nrecovery cannot be expected before\nspring and meanwhile foreign\ncountries face a hard winter. Un\nemployment in Germany increased\nto 3,250,0<>0 in the past month;\nItaly had 391,000 out of work at\nthe end of September, also an in\ncrease; and 2,200,000 are unem\nployed in Great Britain.\nUnemployment\nWe know that workers\u2019 buying\npower i\u00ab now about nine billion\ndollars below last year\u2019s level and\nthat this loss is equivalent to all\nthe goods our factories produce in I\nseven weeks. In other words, pro\nductive activity, trade and trans\nportation must be limited in an\namount equal to tK_ closing of all\nfactories in the United States for\nnearly two months. But even this\nhuge curtailment does not repre\nsent the full shrinkage of demand.\nFor the 20 million wage earners\nwho have jobs know that lay off\nmay come to them at any moment\nand are cutting down their pur\nchases to save morley.lf each wage\nearner were to reduce his buying\nby even II, the loss would be\nequal to the w ages of 250,000 men\nfor one month, or to the entire\nproduct of the canning industry for\ntwo weeks. Reductions like these\ncontinued over a period of time\nhelp create a major depression\nIn the coming winter we look\nforward to unemployment much\nworse than at any time this year.\nAlready in November as many un\nion members were out of work as\nin the worst month last winter.\nUsually the severe winter unera\nployment does not begin till Janu\nary. Unemployment usually rises\nrapidly from November to the\npeak in February or March. Both\n1928 and 1929 rose sharply upward\nafter Novemb* r. If unemployment\nUp-to-the-Minute\nModes\nPrepared Especially for This\nNewspaper\n\u00a9E-XCfcLLA\n1-332*\nE/3324\nA FROCK COSTING ABOUT\n$3.01 USES CHALLIS\nFor a little girl's winter frock, noth\ning is better than challig. It is warin'\narul lightweight, the patterns arej\ndainty, and the colors soft. Here the!\ndesign is accented by a light blue band\napplied in an unusual surplice line,\nthe color being repeated in a fuzzy\nlittle beret. Of course the skirt is\npleated\u2014with box-pleats front and\nback. Size 6 requires\nyards 32-inch challis\nat $1.00....$2.13\nyard 32-inch contrasting\nat $1.00.38\nFindings .30\nFxcella Pattern.20\nTotaling about....,.$3.01\nFxcella Pattern No. 3324. Sizes 2,\n4, 6 and 8 years, 20 cents.\nrises as usual we may expect at\nleast 5,000,000 out of work by\nFebruary and a los9 in buying\npower of three billion dollar* more.\n\u201cHuy Now\u201d Campaign*\nEfforts to \u201cbreak the buyers\nstrike\u201d have been launched in a\nnumber of citie* to stimulate bus\niness and help employment. The\ntheory is that those who have not!\nsuffered from the depression\nshould abandon \u201cfalse\u201d economy\nand \u201cbuy now\u201d* Campaigns have\nsucceeded in stimulating trade at\nleast temporarily but their perma\nnent value is doubted for three\nreasons.\n1. Depression always bringe dis-1\norganization of prices. Price do-j\ndines are general, but some prices\nfall faster than other* and the eco\nnomic balance is destroyed. Manu\nfacturers' prices have fallen faster\nand farther than retail prices,\nfarmers\u2019 prices farthest of all.\nThus the price worker* pay for the\niT'iiitfhilfil i\nAr^enta Bottling Works\nThomaa E. Jonen, Mgr.\nALL KINDS OF SOPr DRINKS\nPhone 4-3435\n?12 Magnolia Street\nNorth Little Rock. Ark.\n--fr -1,rCT~^\nInsure With\nFRED R0SSNER SON\n315 Weat Markham Street\nLittle Rock. Ark.\nW.WAWAW\nSHERRY\nCLEANERS\nAND DYERS\n812 Broadway\nPhone 7373\n14 YEARS\nEXPERIENCE\nGregg and Dan\nWWWVWVWMAMrt/WW\nHelping Build Arkanaa*\nEAT MORE\nSYRUP\nMaple Drip Breakfast\nJoy Honey Drip\nLittle Rock Syrup Co.\n416 Victory. Phono 4-2279\nRefresh Your Self\nDrink\nIN STERILIZED BOTTLES\nCOCA COLA BOTTLING CO.\nLittle Kock, Ark.\nBack of Butter-Nut Bread and\nCakes Is Meyers\u2019 16 Years\nof Baking Experience\nTry this rich, sweet bread as toast. Kou will\nnever change. Its richness ia unequalled and\nthe sweet flavor is only rivalled by the appe\ntizing odor from the sanitary wrapper. Baked\nalways under the personal supervision of Cbaa.\nMeyer.\nMeyers\u2019\nBUTTER-NUT\nBREAD\nMeyers\u2019\nHOLSUM\nBREAD\nAMERICAN BAKERY\nCHAS. T. MEYERS. Owner and Manager\n1217-19 21-23 West Seventh Street\nnecessities of living Uv declined\nonly 6 per cent since October a\nyear ago, while manufacturers\u2019\nprices are 12 per cent lower and\nfarmers\u2019 prices 14 per cent lower.\nCost of living has declined very\nlittle in comparison with the\nshrinkage in workers income.\nWorkers buying power is now 24\nper cent beiow last year and coat\nof living only G per cent lower* It\nis therefore impossible for workers\nto support trade by their buying\nuntil prices come down further.\nEveryone is seeking bargains and\nrightly so. Stores which have re\nduced prices to bargain levels re\nport a flood of buying. Buyers who\n\u201cbuy now\u201d should hunt bargains.\n2. The lasting increase in buying\nwhich can finally pull us out of\nthe depression must bo based on\nconfidence. Employers could do far\nmore to stimulate trade by assur\ning their employes steady work\nthrough the winter. Employers and\nmerchants are not showing their\nconfidence in business improve\nment by increasing their trade ac\ntivity- Why should the man in the\nstreet bear the brunt?\n3. Installment buying has de\ncreased this year. In automobiles,\nthe value of installment sales for\nthe first eight months was 22 per\ncent below last year. Some key\nindustries depend very largely on\ninstallment purchases to sell their\ngoods. Insecurity of jobs makes\nworkers very reluctant to commit\nthemselves for long time pay\nments. Hera again, if employers\nwere to guarantee work they would\nhave more customers. Wage cuts\nare also a serious problem. More\nfirms cut wages in October than\nSeptember, but they were smaller\ncompanies and fewer workers were\naffected* The figures are ns fol\nlows. Firms cutting wages: August\n133, September 87, October 118;\nemployes affected. August 2l;729;\nSeptember 10,884, October 9,817.\nOrganizing for Ontrol\nEvery trade unionist knows that\norganization is essential for order-!\ned progress. When depression\ncame, individuals, whether wage\nearners or business men, were\nhelpless to control their problems.\nTake Your Medicine With You\nChocolate coated tablet*. Juet aa effec\ntive as the liquid. 98 out of 100 repon\nbenefit.\nSold at drug Jfores\nLydiaE.Pinkham's.\nVegetable Compound\nNot How Cheap, But How Good! i\nOur Shoes Stay Fixed\nWonder State Shoe\nShop\n2715 Prospect\n111 Weat 3rd Phona 4-5096\n5-In*I MARKET\nWE DELIVER\nVejreUblen, Grocerle*.\nFruit., Fish\nrhon* 4-8700 51\u00bb Center St.\nW. G. Brown\nWith demnnd shrinking, employer*\nwere forced to curtail production.\nCurtailment meant lay off and and\nlay off meant more curtailment\nand so the vicious circle grew.\nEfforts to organize against un\nemployment are now taking placa\non a nation wide scale. The magni\ntude of Colonel Woods\u2019 task aa\nchairman of the National Emer\ngency Committee for Employment\nmakes it impossible to progress\nrapidly- Although unemployment is\nby no means under control as yet,\nthe progress already made is grat\nifying. Local unemployment com\nmittees are taking hold and get,\nting cooperation of all groups}\nwork is provided by public con\nstruction of work in parka and\nstreets, and by employers who ara\ncooperating to take on more men;\nexchanges have found jobs for\nthousands in the last month; relief\nfunds are being collected.\nA striking fact is becoming evi\nj dent m tliis campaign against un\nemployment. Those cities which\nj have had unemployment commit\ntees for several years to study th*\ni problem and organize control, are\nmeeting their situation with much\ngreater success than thoso relying\nI on emergency measures. If our ex\nperience in this crisis is to count\nfor progress, emergency commit*\ntees must develop into permanent\norganizations for control of depres\nsion forces.\nBuilding Costs Decline\nA favorite argument against\nwage increases is that they in\ncrease costs. Wages can rise while\ncosts decline\nBuilding costs rises far mori\nrapidly than wages up to 1020.\nAlter 1023 building costs declined\nor remain stable while the wage*\nrose. Costs have been lowered by\nefficiency and by falling prices of\nmaterials.\nThe building situation thi*\nmonth is about the same as last\nmonth when allowance is made for\nseasonal changes. Trade review*\nare urging contractors to build novr\nto profit by low prices.\nON\nKuusun\n2 to 15 Years\nLess Interest\nQuick Action\nHome Folks\nSERVICE\nBattery and Electric Shop\nWillard Uattertaa\nGenuine Parts. Prompt Serrlce\nVeadol Motor Oil\nC. LKELLOGG\nn**o mu\nJ*\u00bb Thlr\u00ab. KoMh UtU*\nC. E. SHARPE\n251 B. 16th Phone 9765\nHEALTH ATORIUM\nSweat Baths and Massags\nRecommended for\nRheumatism, Neuritis\nand all nervous ailments.\nBONDED INSURED\nCall Us for Your Next Moving Job\nJ. E. THOMPSON MOTOR EXPRESS\n314 Scott Street\nPhones 4-3768 Little Rock, Ark*\nA Ride is ihe New Chevrolet Six Tells a\nWonderful Story!\ntconomieat Transportation\nn\nI CH EVROLET\nCall Ua for Demonstration\nSmoother\u2014Faster\u2014better\nCRITZ CHEVROLET CO.\n300-306 We*l 3rd St.\nPhone 9304 North Little Rock","height":"21112","width":"17548"}}
